SOQL vs. SOSL

They solve different problems, and the cleanest way to hold the distinction is: SOQL retrieves records; SOSL searches text.

SOQL (Salesforce Object Query Language) queries one object at a time (plus its relationships) and filters on exact field values. 
You know the object, you know the fields, you're asking "give me the records where these conditions are true." 
It queries all fields regardless of whether they're indexed for search, and it's what you use for anything precise — WHERE Industry = 'Tech' AND AnnualRevenue > 1000000.

SOSL (Salesforce Object Search Language) does full-text search across multiple objects at once. 
You're not filtering on a specific field value; you're looking for a term appearing anywhere in the searchable text of the records. 
It hits a search index rather than scanning field values, which is why it's far more efficient for keyword-style lookups across long-text fields.

Here's the same "find Acme" intent in both, to make the shape concrete:

apex
// SOQL — one object, field-value match, LIKE scans
List<Account> a = [SELECT Id, Name FROM Account WHERE Name LIKE '%Acme%'];

// SOSL — many objects, indexed text search
List<List<sObject>> results = [
    FIND 'Acme*' IN NAME FIELDS
    RETURNING Account(Id, Name), Contact(Id, LastName), Lead(Id, Company)
];

The practical decision table:
	                                           SOQL	                                                            SOSL
Purpose	                        Retrieve records by field criteria	                                  Search text across objects
Objects                         per statement	One (+ relationships)	Multiple,                         unrelated
Matching	                      Exact field values, LIKE	                                            Indexed full-text, tokenized
Returns	                        List<sObject>	                                                        List<List<sObject>>
Aggregates / relationships	    Yes (GROUP BY, subqueries)	                                          No
Governor limit / txn	          100 queries	                                                          20 searches
Best at	                        Precise,structured filtering	                                        "Find this word somewhere"


Two things worth internalizing beyond the table. First, SOSL returns a list of lists — one inner list per object in your RETURNING clause, 
in that order — because it's searching several objects simultaneously. 
Second, the performance angle: if you find yourself writing several LIKE '%term%' SOQL queries across different objects to implement a search box, that's the signal to switch to a single SOSL search. 
Leading-wildcard LIKE can't use indexes; SOSL is built on the search index. 
There's also a data-freshness caveat — the search index updates asynchronously, so a record created microseconds ago might not be findable via SOSL yet, whereas SOQL sees it immediately.
