Relationship queries

Relationship queries let you traverse the associations between objects in a single query instead of issuing separate queries and stitching results together in Apex. They come in two directions, and the direction dictates the syntax.

Child-to-parent (traversing "up") — from a record to the record it belongs to. You use dot notation on the relationship field, up to 5 levels deep. A Contact belongs to an Account, so:

apex
List<Contact> contacts = [
    SELECT Id, LastName, Account.Name, Account.Owner.Email
    FROM Contact
    WHERE Account.Industry = 'Technology'
];
System.debug(contacts[0].Account.Name);

Each Contact carries its parent Account inline. Note you can even filter on parent fields in the WHERE.

Parent-to-child (traversing "down") — from a record to the collection of records that belong to it. You use a nested subquery, and you reference the children by the relationship name (usually the plural for standard objects):

apex
List<Account> accts = [
    SELECT Id, Name,
        (SELECT Id, LastName FROM Contacts WHERE Email != null)
    FROM Account
];
for (Account a : accts) {
    for (Contact c : a.Contacts) {   // the child list rides along
        System.debug(a.Name + ' -> ' + c.LastName);
    }
}

The naming rule that trips everyone up: child-to-parent for custom relationships uses __r (e.g. Invoice__r.Name) even though the field is __c, 
and the parent-to-child subquery uses the relationship name (typically Line_Items__r), not the object API name (Line_Item__c). 
When Salesforce says "didn't understand the relationship," it's almost always this naming issue.

Why this matters so much in Apex: relationship queries are a bulkification and governor-limit tool. 
Instead of querying Accounts and then querying Contacts in a loop (which blows your query limit), one relationship query pulls both in a single count against your 100-query budget.
