Polymorphic relationships

A polymorphic relationship is a lookup that can point to more than one type of object. The parent isn't fixed to a single sObject type — different records can have parents of different types.

The canonical examples are standard fields:

Task.WhatId / Event.WhatId — a task's "related to" can be an Account, Opportunity, Case, or a custom object.
Task.WhoId / Event.WhoId — can point to a Contact or a Lead.
Lead.OwnerId, Case.OwnerId, etc. — an owner can be a User or a Queue (Group).

Because the type varies per record, you handle it specially in SOQL using the TYPEOF clause (SOQL polymorphism), which lets you select different fields depending on what the related record actually is:

apex
List<Task> tasks = [
    SELECT Id, Subject,
        TYPEOF What
            WHEN Account THEN Name, Industry, AnnualRevenue
            WHEN Opportunity THEN Amount, StageName, CloseDate
            ELSE Id, Name
        END
    FROM Task
];

TYPEOF says: "if the What is an Account, give me these Account fields; if it's an Opportunity, give me those Opportunity fields." 
You can't just write What.Amount unconditionally, because that field only exists when the parent is an Opportunity.

In Apex code, you then check the concrete type at runtime before casting — because the compiler can't know it:

apex
for (Task t : tasks) {
    if (t.What instanceof Account) {
        Account a = (Account) t.What;
        System.debug('Account: ' + a.Name);
    } else if (t.What instanceof Opportunity) {
        Opportunity o = (Opportunity) t.What;
        System.debug('Opp amount: ' + o.Amount);
    }
}

You can also filter polymorphic relationships by type using the special Type qualifier in a WHERE clause:

apex
List<Task> accountTasks = [
    SELECT Id, Subject, What.Name
    FROM Task
    WHERE What.Type = 'Account'
];

The mental model: a normal lookup is a single-type foreign key; a polymorphic lookup is a foreign key whose target type is data, so both SOQL (TYPEOF) and Apex (instanceof + cast) need a branching mechanism to deal with the type varying record by record.

A tidy way to connect all three: relationship queries are how SOQL traverses associations, 
polymorphic relationships are the special case where the association's type isn't fixed (needing TYPEOF), and SOSL sits outside this entirely as the text-search tool for when you don't know the object or you're searching keywords across many. 
